The formula

says the elements in the "n" row of Pascal's triangle always add up to 2 raised to the "n" power. This is obtained from the binomial theorem () by setting "x" = 1 and "y" = 1. The formula also has a natural combinatorial interpretation: the left side sums the number of subsets of {1...,"n"} of sizes "k" = 0,1...,"n", giving the total number of subsets. (That is, the left side counts the power set of {1...,"n"}.) However, these subsets can also be generated by successively choosing or excluding each element 1...,"n"; the "n" independent binary choices (bit-strings) allow a total of formula_58 choices. The left and right sides are two ways to count the same collection of subsets, so they are equal. 

